AB  - Being mainly an agricultural country the economy of India and its growth
mainly depends on the vagaries of the weather and in particular the
extreme weather events. India with a land of unique climatic regime due
to several characteristic features, including (i) two monsoon seasons
(south-west and north-east) leading to drought & flood condition,
active and break cycle of monsoon and also heavy rainfall leading to
flash flood and landslides, (ii) two cyclone seasons (pre and
post-monsoon cyclone seasons), (iii) hot weather season characterized by
severe thunderstorms, dust storms and heat waves, (iv) cold weather
season characterized by violent snow storms in the Himalayan regions,
cold waves and fog. The socio-economic impacts of the extreme weather
events such as floods, droughts, heavy rainfall, cyclones, hail storm,
