AB  - Hydrological assessment is critical to the successful implementation of
adaption measures. In this study, projections of seven global
circulation models (GCMs) associated with high and medium-low
Representative Concentration Pathways (RCP 8.5 and RCP 4.5) for the
period 2021-2040 and 2081-2100 were adopted to assess changes on runoffs
in the Gilgel Abbay watershed, the upper Blue Nile basin. A weather
generator was employed to generate daily temperature and precipitation
to drive a hydrological model for impact assessment. Despite the
projected magnitude of changes varied among different GCMs and RCPs,
increasing runoffs in wet-season and decreasing in dry-season are
observed in both periods, mainly attributed to the change in projected
precipitation. Such changes are profound in cases of RCP 8.5 with
respect to those of RCP 4.5 and in cases of 2081-2100 with respect to
those of 2021-2040. Although the increasing runoffs would provide
greater inflow to Lake Tana, the increase of precipitation in wet-season
would imply a higher possibility of flash floods. On the other hand,
decrease runoffs in dry-season further intensify existing shortage of
irrigation water demand. These changes will have deleterious
consequences on the economic wellbeing of the country and require
successful implementation of adaption measures to reduce vulnerability.
