AB  - The design of hydraulic structures and flood risk management is often
based on instantaneous peak flow (IPF). However, available flow time
series with high temporal resolution are scarce and of limited length. A
correct estimation of the IPF is crucial to reducing the consequences
derived from flash floods, especially in Mediterranean countries. In
this study, empirical methods to estimate the IPF based on maximum mean
daily flow (MMDF), artificial neural networks (ANN), and adaptive
neuro-fuzzy inference system (ANFIS) have been compared. These methods
have been applied in 14 different streamflow gauge stations covering the
diversity of flashiness conditions found in Peninsular Spain.
Root-mean-square error (RMSE), and coefficient of determination (R-2)
have been used as evaluation criteria. The results show that: (1) the
Fuller equation and its regionalization is more accurate and has lower
error compared with other empirical methods; and (2) ANFIS has
demonstrated a superior ability to estimate IPF compared to any
empirical formula.
