T1  - Specificities and risk due to `flash floods' in the north of France (Parisian Basin)
A1  - Douvinet, Johnny
A1  - Delahaye, Daniel
Y1  - 2010///
PD  - 
AB  - The aim of this article is to review the current knowledge on flash
floods occurring at the end of the spring or during the summer on the
loamy plateaus of the Parisian Basin, in northwestern France.
Classically named muddy floods', such hydrological hazards are
significant as they cause losses of life and significant damage on
buildings and infrastructures. However, they still remain poorly
documented. We propose here to precise their characteristics by studying
flash floods events i) at the local scale thanks to several systematic
investigations on various catchments and ii) at the regional scale using
a specific database recording 269 events on 189 catchments between 1983
and 2005. We focused on material and human damage but not on the main
triggering factors that could explain their occurrence. Results
highlight that these streamflows are characterized by sub-torrential
dynamics, with high sediment contents and time-responses to high
rainfalls (>50 nun in less than 15 h) of less than one hour. Most of the
basins (<40 km(2)) are dry valleys, i.e., permanent stream-flow does not
normally exist during normal periods. Diffusive runoff rapidly shifts to
concentrated runoff, generating high-incised gullies over short
distances. Erosive forms with a depth of several meters and a lateral
extension exceeding 10 m are observed in compact loamy soils but the
major incisions generally appear at the outlet of 1st- or 2nd-order
basins. The morphological component explains this paradox. Because of
high-slopes and a rapid steep sidedness, runoff energy compensates the
low amount of water. Thalwegs of 3rd- or 4th-order basins are therefore
more adapted to evacuate important discharges (weak slope, large
channel). Consequently, they decrease the erosive capacity of
streamflows. High specific discharges (ranging from 1 to 2
m(3).s(-1).km(-2)) and high specific stream powers (from 22 to 511
W/m(2)) are linked to major morphogenic impacts on these small-sized
basins. The final part of tins paper discusses the risk generated by
flash floods on local population. If events and damage are rarely
observed on similar catchments, they are frequent on a regional scale
with 8 to 9 events observed per year in the studied areas.
