T1  - Measuring surface flow concentrations using a cellular automaton metric: a new way of detecting potential impacts of flash floods in sedimentary context
A1  - Douvinet, Johnny
A1  - Delahaye, Daniel
A1  - Langlois, Patrice
Y1  - 2013///
PD  - 
AB  - This paper aims to investigate a new way of calculating potential
impacts of flash floods. Mapping surface flow concentrations, using a
new metric based on a cellular automaton RuiCells, is shown to
qualitative align with observed and known instances of damage caused by
flash floods in 5 small `dry valleys' located in northern France
(Parisian Basin). The model used is driven according to a set of three
deterministic hydrological rules governing surface water flow. Numerical
simulations enable the assessment of the relations between the
organisation of thalwegs networks and surfaces for a given basin form.
An index of concentration (IC) allows detecting the confluences in
upstream of which networks and surfaces are spatially well organised. A
strong correlation between observed damage, field experiments, local
knowledge and maps of IC index exists as simulations underline many
places where flash floods induce important material or human damage and
where further surface flow concentration results in highly-incised
gullies. In rare cases no validation is possible because nobody can
confirm the degradations. Regarding these methodological investigations,
the place of land use and of such tools for assessing flash flooding in
`dry valleys' in northern France is discussed. Prospects made in other
basins also offer promising results, so such information will help risk
managers to prevent possible damage in case of future flash floods, and
contribute towards defining sensitive areas as mandated in the European
Water Framework Directive (2007/60/EC) and as is now currently being
attempted.
