AB  - On 25 October 2011, heavy rainfall affected an area of ca. 1000km(2)
between eastern Liguria and northern Tuscany (northwest Italy). The
event caused floods, hundreds of shallow landslides, four casualties and
severe structural and economic damage in Monterosso and Vernazza
villages. The distribution of geo-hydrological processes triggered by
rainfall in relation to land-use was analyzed in the Vernazza catchment.
Both, an inventory map of geo-hydrological processes and a land-use map
were prepared through air photo-analysis and field surveys; a derivative
map combining these two outputs provides insight into the relationships
between geo-hydrological processes and land-use. The density of shallow
landslides (n/km(2)) and the frequency of erosional processes (%) are
higher in terraced areas compared to other land-use classes. The study
highlights the high vulnerability of agricultural terraces which, over
the centuries, have been a fundamental tool for the prevention and
control of erosional processes and slope instability.
