areas, located in geo-environmental contexts whose balances become
unstable because of natural physical changes (eg.: changing climate
conditions) and/or changes induced by human interventions (construction
of infrastructures, represented by someone, in the pejorative way, with
the term ``overbuilding{''}).
The city, as anintegrated system of infrastructures, may be exposed not
only to the critical geo-environmental hazard of the site where they are
located (eg. coastal erosion, slope instability, subsidence, flooding,
etc.) but also to those generated by boundary areas, sometimes even at a
considerable distance.
The recent meteorological history shows a growing incidence of
hydrological and hydrogeological events (such as, for example, storms in
