AB  - In a globally warming world, subtropical regions are generally expected
to become drier while the tropics and mid-high latitudes become wetter.
In line with this, Southwest China, close to 25A degrees N, is expected
to become increasingly prone to drought if annual mean precipitation
decreases. However, despite this trend, changes in the temporal
distribution of moisture supply might actually result in increased
extreme rainfall in the region, whose climate is characterized by
distinct dry and wet seasons. Using hourly and daily gauge observations,
rainfall intensity changes since 1971 are examined for a network of 142
locations in the region. From the analysis, dry season changes are
negligible but wet season changes exhibit a significantly strong
downward trend {[}-2.4% (10 yr)(-1)], particularly during the past 15
years {[}-17.7% (10 yr)(-1)]. However, the intensity of events during
the wettest of 5% hours appears to steadily increase during the whole
period {[}1.4% (10 yr)(-1)], tying in with government statistical
reports of recent droughts and flooding. If the opposing trends are a
consequence of a warming climate, it is reasonable to expect the
contradictory trend to continue with an enhanced risk of flash flooding
in coming decades in the region concerned.
