AB  - At present times, an intensification of the hydrological risk can be
observed, and during the last 10 years, several flash floods with a
probability greater than 1% have occurred on numerous, small-sized
drainage basins in Romania. The Ozana drainage basin is reduced in
dimensions, but has a very large hydrologic potential. On the river
valley, there are a total of 11 villages, out of which 9 have a
pronounced risk to flooding, acording to the data given by the Flood
Directive 2007/60/CE. The purpose of this paper is to identify the time
intervals characterized by positive or negative pluviometric anomalies,
and the frequency that they have. There are two main categories of
hydrological risks, associated with the drainage basin: first of all,
there are the floodrelated risks, mostly caused by extreme precipitation
events; and second of all, the periods characterized by drought, during
times with water deficit. The latter has been observed to occur
downstream of Dumbrava village (at 11 km from the confluence with
Moldova river), and its negative effects involve the degrading of local
ichthyofauna, groundwater depletion, and the reduction in quantity of
the water sources. In order to identify the periods with anomalies,
compared to the average precipitation values, and also to their
frequency, the Standardized Precipitation Index (SPI) has been
calculated. SPI was calculated for a period of 36 years (1977 - 2013),
at different time intervals (1, 3, 6, 12 months). The analysis has
revealed anomalies varying from -3 to + 3, representing time spans with
both excess and deficit in pluviometric recordings. In order to identify
the variability periods, as well as the couple of years, which can be
characterised through the same type of anomalies, the Fourier analysis
has been applied. By calculating the Fourier Transform, predictions can
be made on the return time of a certain type of climatic influence.
